               <msContents>
                  <summary>Mahzor according to the Western Asheknazi rite, for the high holidays and Sukkot</summary>
                  <msItem> 
                     <title xml:lang="he">מחזור מנהג אשכנז המערבי לימים נוראים ולסוכות</title>
                     <title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Maḥzor minhag Ashkenaz ha-maʻaravi le-yamim noraim ṿele-Sukkot</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="he">Hebrew</textLang>
                  </msItem>                  
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc>
                        <support>parchment</support>
                        <extent>ff. 314</extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Ashkenazic square script</summary>
                     <handNote>The names Judah (<locus>fol. 194r</locus>) and Isaac (<locus>fols. 40v, 195r</locus>) are pointed out on fols. 194r and 195r by means of allusive illustrations. It is possible that Judah was the original owner and the scribe Isaac entered the names of Judah's sons into the liturgy.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
